### Why this is more maintainable

- **Single source of truth for tokens**: All color and elevation decisions are centralized in `@layer tokens`; dark mode only remaps tokens, not component styles. This keeps per‑component CSS short and theme‑agnostic. fileciteturn0file0  
- **Scoped modules**: Each “block” (Header/Nav, Hero, Split, Programs, Testimonials, FAB) is findable and self‑documented, with media queries collocated to the component they affect. This mirrors the structure in your HTML (e.g., `.mobile-menu`, `.t-track`, `.hero-cta`, etc.), making cross‑navigation trivial. fileciteturn0file1  
- **Less risk from later edits**: With layers, future additions can slot into `components` or `sections` without unexpectedly overriding tokens or base styles.

> **Browser support note**: `@layer` is supported in all current evergreen browsers. If you must support older engines (Safari < 15.4, Firefox < 97, Chrome < 99), remove the `@layer` wrappers while keeping the same section headings — you’ll keep the organization benefits without the cascade guarantees.

If you want, I can also split this into **physical files** (e.g., `tokens.css`, `base.css`, `components/*.css`, `sections/*.css`) and generate a `@import` (or single build artifact) to match your deployment stack. The new CSS maps 1:1 onto the sections of your current `index.html`, so it’s straightforward to maintain as you add pages. fileciteturn0file1
